# Line-ending policy — keep the working tree LF on EVERY OS.
#
# The repo stores text as LF and the .editorconfig + CI gate enforce LF. Without
# this file, Git for Windows (core.autocrlf=true by default) rewrites the tree to
# CRLF on checkout, so the LF validator fails on ~every file when run from a
# Windows terminal. `eol=lf` pins the working-tree ending regardless of the user's
# autocrlf setting, so the gate holds identically on Windows, Linux and macOS.
* text=auto eol=lf

# The one carve-out the .editorconfig also makes: Windows batch files, which the
# Windows shell expects as CRLF.
*.cmd text eol=crlf
*.bat text eol=crlf

# Binary assets git must never line-ending-convert (auto usually detects these,
# but be explicit so a stray rule can't corrupt them).
*.png  binary
*.jpg  binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif  binary
*.ico  binary
*.gz   binary
*.zip  binary
